### 2. Added `MANDT` to the JOIN Predicate
The original join used only `BELNR + GJAHR + BUKRS`, leaving `MANDT` — the first column of `PK_BKPF(MANDT, BUKRS, BELNR, GJAHR)` — unbound. This prevented an Index Unique Scan and forced a full table scan on BKPF. Adding `k.MANDT = b.MANDT` completes the full PK lookup, making every BKPF probe a guaranteed single-row unique scan.

### 3. Eliminated Redundant Subquery Layers
The original had three nesting levels (innermost filter → join subquery → outer CASE). Collapsing to a single query level removes two intermediate result materializations, reduces parse overhead, and gives the optimizer full visibility into all predicates and join conditions simultaneously for a better overall plan.
